@node description "Description"

	ArexxGuide online help for CygnusEd v3.5+

	Press a key and the script will search ArexxGuide for the node
	corresponding to the word under the cursor and show it on CygnusEd's
	public screen (Or another public screen).

	In addition to ArexxGuide arx_help.ced will also search any other
	crossreference (xref) files that you have installed. So you can also
	get online help for other Arexx function libraries or use it as a
	simple AutoDoc lookup tool.

	Arx_help.ced is also capable of finding function names when they have
	an alias. Eg: The functions from rmh.library - if you want help for
	the alias "rmh_readargs()" arx_help.ced will display the correct
	node, "readargs()"

@endnode 
@node requirements "Requirements"

	@{u}ArexxGuide 2.0a@{uu} (Aminet: util/rexx/ARexxGuide2_0A.lha).

	Note: ArexxGuide comes in two flavors. One that uses ReqTools
	requesters to show glossary text and one where the glossary is
	incorporated into the guide itself. Arx_help.ced has no glossary
	support so it works best with the above version.

	@{u}CygnusEd 3.5+@{uu}

	Note: One of the @{"configuration" link configuration} options require v4.18 or higher. 
	But you can disable it if you haven't upgraded.

	@{u}MiniView@{uu} (Aminet: text/hyper/MiniView-37.1.lha)

	The smallest AmigaGuide viewer. Included with this archive in the c
	drawer. Just copy it to somewhere in your path (eg: to C:). MiniView is
	pure, so if you have a slow Amiga, it might speed things up sligtly if you
	make it resident.

	Arx_help.ced should work with any version of AmigaDos capable of
	running CygnusEd 3.5. But it really works best with Workbench 3.5
	because the Arexx interface of the amigaguide.datatype has been
	improved and bugfixed.

@endnode
@node installation "Installation"

	Copy arx_help.ced to rexx:
	Copy c/MiniView to somewhere in your path (eg: to C:).

	Install the script on one of the FKeys in CED or bind it to any other
	key with a long invocation macro like this:
	- Start long-term invocation macro.
	- Select 'HELP' (Or something else) as hotkey.
	- Select Send Dos/Arexx command.
	- Enter 'run >nil rx rexx: arx_help.ced' in the requester.
	- Finish the macro and save it.

	If you want to have the AmigaGuide window open on another publicscreen
	than CED's you can do this: 'run >nil rx rexx: arx_help.ced <pubscr>.
	I have 'HELP' setup as the regular 'arx_help.ced' and 'shift-HELP' as
	'arx_help.ced Workbench'.

	Create a directory somewhere on your harddisk to store your xref files.
	Now copy the xref files you need from the xref directory in this archive
	to the directory you just created.
	Even better: Create a 'not_in_use' directory in the directory above. Copy
	the xref files you @{u}don't@{uu} need to this directory. This way you 
	can easily switch xref files around if you wish to - arx_help.ced will 
	detect gny changes made to the xref directory and add or remove xref 
	files	as necessary.

	Don't forget to @{" configure " link configuration} arx_help.ced so it knows where to find your 
	xref directory.

@endnode
@node configuration "Configuration"

	Load the script into your text editor and edit the configuration section.

	@{u}xrefdir@{uu}

	The xrefdir directory will be scanned and any files found will be loaded
	as a xref file. You must specify this and the directory must contain xref
	files only - otherwise you won't get any online help.

	@{u}guidedirs@{uu}

	The Amigaguide document will be searched for in these directories. 
	Separate directories with a space.
	If you don't specify any directories arx_help.ced will fall back on the
	amigaguide default search path.

	@{u}leaveroom@{uu}

	Make CygnusED leave x number of lines free for the Amigaguide window. This
	option requires CED v4.18 or higher, else set it to 0. A value of 13 looks
	nice on a 800x600 screen.
	Note: This option only works if you open CED on it's own public screen. If
	you open CED on eg. Workbench or a custom screen it is simply ignored.
	Note: This option doesn't seem to work when using WinUAE. 

@endnode
@node usage "Usage notes"

	Have a look at the @{" installation " link installation} section for how to open the help window 
	on another public screen then CED's.

	If you start the script while the cursor is on an empty line, you will
	be presented with a string requester. Just type any in any Arexx
	keyword, press OK, and the according help text will pop up.

	You add xref files simply by moving them into the @{" xref directory " link installation}. And
	remove xref files by, well, removing them :-). Removing xref files
	requires Workbench 3.5 to work properly though.

	If you use the @{" leaveroom " link configuration} option to let CED leave some space for the guide
	window on it's screen, it's a good idea to spend some time making the
	window fit the 'room' perfectly. When you're satisfied select 'save as
	default' from the guide menu to save the window position.

@endnode
@node xref "xref files"

	Here is a list of the other xref files I have included. The ArexxGuide
	xref file is the same as the one included in the ArexxGuide 2.0 archive.

	@{" ARx_Guide.xref      " link xref/ARx_Guide.xref/main} ArexxGuide xref file.
	@{" autodocs.xref       " link xref/autodocs.xref/main} AutoDocs crossreference.
	@{" RexxLocalDates.xref " link xref/RexxLocalDates.xref/main} Anders Wegge Jakobsen's rexxlocaldates.library.
	@{" RexxReqTools.xref   " link xref/RexxReqTools.xref/main} Rafael D'Halleweyn's rexxreqtools.library.
	@{" rexxtricks.xref     " link xref/rexxtricks.xref/main} Jürgen Kohrmeyer's rexxtricks.library.
	@{" rmh.xref            " link xref/rmh.xref/main} Alfonso Ranieri's excellent rmh.library.

	Read @{" installation " link installation} for how to install the xref files and get online
	help for the corresponding libraries.

	With the included makexref.rexx script you can create your own Amigaguide
	xref files. Here's how it works:

	rx makexref.rexx <path to .guide file>
	Eg: rx makexref.rexx txt:arexx/rexxreqtools.guide

	This will create a file called txt:arexx/rexxreqtools.xref. You must
	edit this file and remove all entries that you don't want included in
	the online help system (Author info, copyright notices etc). Have a look
	at the rexxreqtools.xref files in the makexref drawer and in the xref
	drawer to see the difference between a 'raw' and an edited xref file.

@endnode
